text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Facial Expression in ASl%0a%0a:Author: meturner%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aExploring the importance of facial expression in communication using American Sign Language.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn American Sign Language, meaning is expressed through gestures of the body—this refers to, most obviously, the movement of the hands and arms, but facial expressions (sometimes called “tone of face”) are vital to communication as well. The aspects of ASL that do not involve the hands are called non-manual, and are just as important for an ASL learner as the gestures themselves. In many cases, changing the facial expression that accompanies a sign can modify or completely change the meaning. %0a%0aIntricacies of meaning that, in spoken English, are conveyed mostly through inflection, are carried by ASL users in their facial expressions. In the CBC article linked below about “Seen and Heard,” for example, the sign for ‘incredible’ can mean ‘awful,’ ‘shocking,’ ‘amazing,’ or ‘impressive,’ based on the signer’s facial expression and attitude. %0a%0aOther examples of this concept include raised eyebrows to indicate a yes-or-no question, different expressions to convey diminution or emphasis of a certain trait (ex. ‘A little angry’ as opposed to ‘furious’), or shaking the head to indicate an opposite meaning (as in ‘not hungry’). There are also signs whose hand gestures are nearly identical and which are distinguished only by facial expression, such as “rolling on the floor laughing” and “seizure,” as mentioned in the third linked article. This differentiation of definition is certainly stark, and illustrates how important the expression is to the communication of meaning. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://www.cbc.ca/arts/it-s-called-sign-language-but-facial-expressions-are-super-important-too-1.4952771%0ahttps://www.lifeprint.com/asl101/pages-layout/facialexpressions.htm%0ahttps://www.lifeprint.com/asl101/topics/facial-expressions-if-you-are-not-using.htm%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221112-221501-378150#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Parallels to spoken language %0a-> - ejwang2%0a-> [-12.11.2022 - 14:15-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221112-221501-378150 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aInteresting observation that inflection in spoken language is the analog of facial expressions in signed language. I'd like to add that facial expressions are contribute significantly to spoken language and may even guide inflection. For instance, since it's easier to communicate when there exists a congruence between the emotion conveyed by our facial expressions and by our inflection, it is often helpful, when seeking to sound a certain way, first to adjust our facial expression to match that feeling. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221112-221501-378150#%0a#foxbegin 221123-174405-688730#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Sarcasm in Sign Language %0a-> - sjdutton%0a-> [-23.11.2022 - 09:44-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221123-174405-688730 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn spoken lanuage, sarcasm is noticed through the change of tone of the speaker. Meanwhile, in sign language, sarcasm can be conveyed through changes in facial expressions or by emphasizing certain signs (speeding up some and slowing down others).  However, signers can have their own unique way of conveying sarcasm. For example, one signer from the University of Manitoba would reverse the sign. This shows that in either language, spoken or signed, it is possible to change the meaning of what you are communicating through sarcasm.%0aSource:https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/university-of-manitoba-researchers-study-how-people-who-are-deaf-understand-sarcasm-1.3382283 %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221123-174405-688730#%0a#foxbegin 221127-201949-881410#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Facial Tracking tech in Sign Language %0a-> - aarnavp%0a-> [-27.11.2022 - 12:19-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221127-201949-881410 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aOn the topic of facial expressions in sign language, new technologies have made it possible to hyper analyze the degree of characteristic facial expressions in overall meaning. In a study conducted in the context of Kazakh-Russo Sign Language, researchers were able to track eyebrow movement to see its correlation with emotion and interrogative questions. This creates the potential to analyze the eyebrow movement from signs within a sentence, and understand the complex system facial expressions play with this larger sign language system. It’s interesting to note the similarities between sign language and spoken language, where facial expressions can apply for multiple different moods within a sentence. %0a%0a1)uib.no/en/hf/136874/complex-system-facial-expressions-sign-language#:~:text="In%2520sign%2520language%252C%2520facial%2520expressions,or%2520when%2520quoting%2520someone%2520else.%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221127-201949-881410#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a(:Title: Facial Expression in ASl:)
